    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>To Treat Women With Respect</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Beth Buschman-Kelly letter lauding Brent Staples's June 26 column on Central Park attacks scores those who spout 'evolutionary' reasons for men's aggression toward women</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I'm so glad that Brent Staples (Editorial Observer, June 26) feels sympathetic to the women in Central Park who were harassed, but there is an increasingly visible segment of the population that wouldn't. This backlash of ''Neanderthals'' -- they wouldn't mind the label -- is spouting ''evolutionary'' reasons for men's aggression. They wish to dominate women in an effort to ''rehabilitate'' men and bring such misbehavior back to the norm.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I'm so glad that Brent Staples (Editorial Observer, June 26) feels sympathetic to the women in Central Park who were harassed, but there is an increasingly visible segment of the population that wouldn't. This backlash of ''Neanderthals'' -- they wouldn't mind the label -- is spouting ''evolutionary'' reasons for men's aggression. They wish to dominate women in an effort to ''rehabilitate'' men and bring such misbehavior back to the norm.</p>
        <p>It's sick and wrongheaded, and threatens all the progress the rest of society -- men and women -- has made.</p>
        <p>BETH BUSCHMAN-KELLY  Cambridge, Mass., June 26, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
